'''Alan Sheridan''' (1934 - 2015) was an English author and translator.
==Life== Born '''Alan Mark Sheridan-Smith''', Sheridan read English at [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]] before spending 5 years in [[Paris]] as English assistant at [[Lycée Henri IV]] and [[Lycée Condorcet]].<ref>[http://errol.oclc.org/laf/n81-150083.html Library of Congress Name Authority File]</ref> Returning to London, he briefly worked in publishing before becoming a freelance translator. He translated works of fiction, history, philosophy, literary criticism, biography and psychoanalysis by [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], [[Jacques Lacan]], [[Michel Foucault]], [[Alain Robbe-Grillet]], [[Robert Pinget]] and many others. He was the first to publish a book in English on Foucault's work and also wrote a biography of [[André Gide]].
