'''''Heart of the Matter''''' is a British television debate series that aired on [[BBC One]] from 1979 to 2000. Presented variously by [[Joan Bakewell]], [[Helena Kennedy]] QC and [[David Jessel]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Sue |last=Summers |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/interview--ms-bakewell-gets-to-the-heart-of-the-matter-the-bbcs-awardwinning-presenter-of-the-old-school-tells-sue-summers-whats-gone-wrong-in-the-corporation-corrected-1436672.html |title=Ms Bakewell gets to the heart of the matter: The BBC's award-winning presenter of the old school tells Sue Summers what's gone wrong in the corporation |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=18 May 1994 |accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> its subject matter was often concerned with [[religion|religious]] or [[ethics|ethical issues]]. Topics covered include subjects as diverse as [[substance abuse]], the effects of [[Anti-personnel mines|anti-personnel landmines]], and [[homosexuality]]. Bakewell would usually chair an in-studio debate in which invited guests would discuss the edition's chosen topic. An edition from 1996 hosted by [[Joan Bakewell]], ''The Heart of the Matter: God Under the Microscope'' featured a debate on science and religion and included as guests [[David Starkey]], [[Mary Warnock]], [[Wentzel van Huyssteen]], [[Richard Dawkins]], Polish Roman Catholic priest and 2008 Templeton Prize winner <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.templetonprize.org/previouswinner.html |title=The Templeton Prize – Previous Winners |publisher=Templetonprize.org |date= |accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref> cosmologist Prof. [[Michał Heller|Michael Heller]], and [[James D. Watson|James Watson]].

''Heart of the Matter'' was broadcast late on Sunday evenings, usually alternating with the similarly-themed ''[[Everyman (TV series)|Everyman]]'', though the latter tended to have more of a religious focus. Both programmes were cancelled<ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew |last=Moore |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/5594549/BBCs-appointment-of-Muslim-as-head-of-religion-is-worrying-Anglicans-warn.html |title=BBC's appointment of Muslim as head of religion is 'worrying', Anglicans warn |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref> in the 2000s following a revamp of BBC output.

